{
  "texts": [
    "Our experiments demonstrate that overestimating the contamination ratio by 5-10% enhances robustness and AUROC.",
    "Specifically, as the rejection ratio increases, the proportion of abnormal instances in the training set decreases, resulting in a more stable and reliable model.",
    "However, an excessively high rejection ratio may exclude a substantial portion of normal data, potentially reducing overall performance.",
    "These results align with our theoretical findings, reinforcing the necessity of aggressive rejection in anomaly detection.",
